-- 
South African Stocks: Anglo American, Avusa, Metorex

-- B y   R o b e r t   B r a n d
-- 
2011-03-28T15:27:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-10/south-african-stocks-anglo-american-bhp-mvelaserve-steinhoff.html
South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index declined for a second day, falling 218.77, or 0.7
percent, to 31,377.12 as of the 5 p.m. close of trading in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified miner that
part-owns the world’s biggest platinum miner, dropped 6 rand, or
1.7 percent, to 349 rand, its biggest drop since March 10, as
copper declined and platinum fell for a third day, losing as
much as 1.2 percent to $1,727.57 an ounce.  Impala Platinum
Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  , the second-biggest producer of the
metal, slumped 5.58 rand, or 2.8 percent, to 192 rand.  Avusa Ltd. (AVU)  , South Africa’s No. 2 newspaper
publisher, climbed to its highest closing price since September
2008, rising 3.89 rand, or 18 percent, after daily newspaper New
Age said  Mvelaphanda Group Ltd. (MVG)   is seeking a financial
backer to buy the shares in Avusa it doesn’t already own.
Mvelaphanda rose 15 cents, or 5.3 percent, to 2.99 rand.  Metorex Ltd. (MTX)  , a coal and base metal miner,
advanced to its highest level since October 2008 after saying it
is in talks which, if successfully concluded, may affect its
share price. The stock climbed 22 cents, or 3.6 percent, to 6.32
rand.  RBA Holdings Ltd. (RBA SJ), the developer of cheap houses,
fell one cent, or 6.3 percent, to 15 cents, its biggest drop in
two weeks. RBA said it sees a full-year loss per share of 10.95
cents per share.  To contact the reporter on this story:
